commitResults.messageBody:
A UniqueMeetingList does not serve a neccessary purpose of the list
preventing any conflicting meetings from added.

Let's replace UniqueMeetingList with NoConflictMeetingList. Most of the
conflicts checking is done via the contains method, which invokes the
Meeting#willConflict method. contains will check specifically for any
conflicting meetings. For remove, conflicts checking is done by an even
stricter remove methods (which uses equals method by java conventions) to enforce no wrongful removal of a Meeting.

The original setMeeting will have prevented any existing meetings from
being edited if they have the same time and date.

By checking if the editedMeeting DOES conflict with the originalMeeting
(and only with the originalMeeting since NoConflictMeetingList enforces
zero conflicts), we can tell if the editedMeeting is the same as the
originalMeeting only with non timing changes (e.g., description
changes).

Let's add a condition to check for conflicts with the original timing.
If the contains evaluates to true, and the conflict is actually with the
originalMeeting's timing, then there is no conflicts as it is just
a simple update to the same exact meeting.

listMeeting currently has no requirement to use a filter. Hence no test for filters is added, only test if list remains unchanged (having everything in the list, nothing filtered).

There are some tests e.g., AddCommandTest which uses ModelStub. These stubs have been updated to include the updated Model interface which has methods to get and update the FilteredMeetingList.

MyInsuRecTest (ClientBookTest) will require adding some test to test this two new methods which will be added in a future commit.

MyInsuRecStub (ClientBookStub) 's constructor is also updated to match one new method for MyInsuRec (ClientBook) (getMeetingList). For now, one of the methods which does not involve checking for meetingList has also been updated appropriately to reflect the change in MyInsuRecStub (ClientBookStub) constructor.

There was no hook from storage to model previously for
NoConflictMeetingList. The main hook is found in
JsonSerializableClientBook#toModelType.

There are significant changes in CommandResults to take note of: 2 new
attributes are defined in order to denote whether the command was client
or meeting specific. These are not in a single attribute as there can be
commands that are not client or meeting specific and we don't want to
change the view unneccessarily (to switch to meeting or client specific).

The change will require all existing commands to use the new constructor
in order for UI to work properly for the command.

Unfortunately, because of the intrinsic behaviour of method overloading,
the constructor for CommandResult is now long with 2 additional
parameters. One solution could be to use factory methods to create
CommandResults. Another could be to use a more awkward parameter
positions (`public CommandResult(boolean isClient, boolean isMeeting,
String feedbackToUser)`).

The logic for switching of panels can be found in MainWindow.java. To
summarise, we simply clear the placeholder and add the panel we need to
the placeholder each time we swap.

commitResults.messageBody:
This bug is relatively insignficant in affecting the program's
usability.

Due to a previous change in CommandSpecific (that removed a null check),
HelpCommand and ExitCommand were both afflicted with this issue.

Hence, a new enum for CommandSpecific was added. This is to specify for
commands that don't have any specificity in which window to show (Exit
and Help currently). The overloaded constructor is also changed to
default to this value.

The switch case in MainWindow is also shifted up. This is not a very
important change as it is unlikely to happen again, but this is to hopefully
prevent a similar issue in the future as we will be able to notice any
exceptions caused by the switch block.

commitResults.messageBody:
Before, entering a negative integer will result in the command usage being displayed.
After this change, entering a negative integer will instead result in the message
"Index is not a non-zero unsigned integer." being displayed.
Entering a positive integer that is out of bounds of the client list will display the more
specific message, "The client index provided could not be found in the list of clients."

commitResults.messageBody:
Before, if we tried editing a meeting, e.g., from 1300 to 1400 and make its start
time 1230, it will give an error that there is a conflicting meeting because it
conflicts with the current version of itself.
After this fix, the meetings list is only checked for conflicts with meetings other
than the one being edited.
